In a Hinduized text the Prodigal Son would himself literally turn into a pig, having gazed at the pigsty so long it gazed back into him, and a Hindu would read the story as being about literal involution. A poetic reading reveals moral meaning, a literal one reveals monstrosity.

A certain Italian baron pointed out the Biblical story of the Prodigal Son who worked as a swineherd and came to crave the pigs' food and the Odysseus episode of the hero's companions succumbing under Circe and being turned into pigs are analogical, even as their language differs

Thinking about how Song of Songs describes the woman as purple-haired so Misato's look in Evangelion is Biblical. The NIV (Non-Inspired Version) tries to cover it up by translating it as "royal tapestry" instead. Probably has to do something w/ the Phoenician purple dye business.

I think the "blue blood" phrase associated with aristocracy probably etymologically has to do with the purple dye of the Phoenicians too, as it was used for the clothing of emperors and kings and such and the snails of which it is produced have blue blood.

Thinking about how one of my friends here hallucinated off nicotine gum and met a couple gargoyles while awake. Any time I have seen gargoyles (alas only carved from stone) I feel at ease and safe, as when one meets a friendly dog when walking in the woods without a companion.

I think Chesterton recorded a real story of a frightened traveler walking through a forest at midnight and being joined by a horrifying black dog which accompanied him to his destination. Later found the woods was full of bandits and there was a legend of a church grim ghost dog.

The above friend mentioned traditional gargoyles are portrayed frog-like, resembling frogs. Maybe a similar case to Blake's The Flea, how frogs look in their true form, in Eden, or in the limbo between worlds. One also always feels spiritually protected in the presence of a frog.
